[src:sbom/continuous-integration] The earliest known work (1989) on continuous integration was the Infuse environment developed by G.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] In 1997, Kent Beck and Ron Jeffries invented extreme programming (XP) while on the Chrysler Comprehensive Compensation System project, including continuous integration.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Beck published about continuous integration in 1998, emphasising the importance of face-to-face communication over technological support.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] In 1999, Beck elaborated more in his first full book on Extreme Programming.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] CruiseControl, one of the first open-source CI tools, was released in 2001.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] In 2010, Timothy Fitz published an article detailing how IMVU's engineering team had built and been using the first practical CD system.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] While his post was originally met with skepticism, it quickly caught on and found widespread adoption as part of the lean software development methodology, also based on IMVU.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] The core activities of CI are that developers co-locate code changes in a shared, integration area frequently and that the resulting integrated codebase is verified for correctness.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] The first part generally involves merging changes to a common version control branch.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] The second part generally involves automated processes including: building, testing and many other processes.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Typically, a server builds from the integration area frequently, i.e. after each commit or periodically, like once a day.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] The server may perform quality control checks such as running unit tests and collect software quality metrics via processes such as static analysis and performance testing.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Build automation tools automate building.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend that a single command should have the capability of building the system.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Automation often includes automating the integration, which often includes deployment into a production-like environment.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] In many cases, the build script not only compiles binaries but also generates documentation, website pages, statistics and distribution media (such as Debian DEB, Red Hat RPM or Windows MSI files).
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] CI requires the version control system to support atomic commits; in other words, all of a developer's changes are handled as a single commit.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] When making a code change, a developer creates a branch that is a copy of the current codebase.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] As other changes are committed to the repository, this copy diverges from the latest version.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] The longer development continues on a branch without merging to the integration branch, the greater the risk of multiple integration conflicts and failures when the developer branch is eventually merged back.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] When developers submit code to the repository they must first update their code to reflect the changes in the repository since they took their copy.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] The more changes the repository contains, the more work developers must do before submitting their own changes.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Eventually, the repository may become so different from the developers' baselines that they enter what is sometimes referred to as "merge hell", or "integration hell", where the time it takes to integrate exceeds the time it took to make their original changes.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI suggest that developers should use test-driven development and to ensure that all unit tests pass locally before committing to the integration branch so that one developer's work does not break another developer's copy.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Incomplete features can be disabled before committing, using feature toggles.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Continuous delivery ensures the software checked in on an integration branch is always in a state that can be deployed to users, and continuous deployment automates the deployment process.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend storing all files and information needed for building in version control (for git a *repository*), and that the system should be buildable from a fresh checkout and not require additional dependencies.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Martin Fowler recommends that all developers commit to the same integration branch.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Developers can reduce the effort of resolving conflicting changes by synchronizing changes with each other frequently, at least daily.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Checking in a week's worth of work risks conflict both in likelihood of occurrence and complexity to resolve.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Relatively small conflicts are significantly easier to resolve than larger ones.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Integrating (committing) changes at least once a day is considered good practice, and more often better.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Building daily, if not more often, is generally recommended.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] The system should build commits to the current working version to verify that they integrate correctly.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] A common practice is to use Automated Continuous Integration, although this may be done manually.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Automated continuous integration employs a continuous integration server or daemon to monitor the revision control system for changes, then automatically run the build process.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] When fixing a bug, it is a good practice to push a test case that reproduces the bug.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] This prevents the fix from being reverted and the bug from reappearing, which is known as a regression.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] The build needs to complete rapidly so that if there is a problem with integration, it is quickly identified.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Having a test environment can lead to failures in tested systems when they deploy in the production environment because the production environment may differ from the test environment in a significant way.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] However, building a replica of a production environment is cost-prohibitive.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Instead, the test environment or a separate pre-production environment ("staging") should be built to be a scalable version of the production environment to alleviate costs while maintaining technology stack composition and nuances.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Within these test environments, service virtualisation is commonly used to obtain on-demand access to dependencies (e.g., APIs, third-party applications, services, mainframes, etc.) that are beyond the team's control, still evolving, or too complex to configure in a virtual test lab.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Making builds readily available to stakeholders and testers can reduce the amount of rework necessary when rebuilding a feature that doesn't meet requirements.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Additionally, early testing reduces the chances that defects survive until deployment.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Finding errors earlier can reduce the amount of work necessary to resolve them.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] All programmers should start the day by updating the project from the repository.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] That way, they will all stay up to date.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] It should be easy to find out whether the build breaks and, if so, who made the relevant change and what that change was.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] Most CI systems allow the running of scripts after a build finishes.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] In most situations, it is possible to write a script to deploy the application to a live test server that everyone can look at.
[src:sbom/continuous-integration] A further advance in this way of thinking is continuous deployment, which calls for the software to be deployed directly into production, often with additional automation to prevent defects or regressions.
[src:sbom/dependency-hell] The dependency issue arises when several packages have dependencies on the same *shared* packages or libraries, but they depend on different and incompatible versions of the shared packages.
[src:sbom/dependency-hell] If the shared package or library can only be installed in a single version, the user may need to address the problem by obtaining newer or older versions of the dependent packages.
[src:sbom/dependency-hell] This, in turn, may break other dependencies and push the problem to another set of packages.
